da\nho Commercial Clubs, is a visitor In.\ntown, having-come here to attend\nthe sessions of the Oregon Develop\nment League. Mr. Atkinson was In\nSalem two and a half years ago .is\na dolegate to the Oregon-Idaho De\nvelopment congress. He Is very\nmuch pleased to see the' phenome\nnal growth made by Salem and com\nplimented the city on Us spirit of\nprogress as shown, during his ab\nsence. Me neavea a great sign 01 ro\nller when Informed by the but man\nthat there was a new hotel In\ntown. Speaking of Southern Idaho,\nMr. Atkinson was very enthusiastic.\nHe stated that Southern Idaho Is\nconcentrating all Its efforts toward\nplacing people on Its raw lands and\nthat they are coming In In larga\nnumbers. He said, \"Idaho \"ts tbe\nlast of the great Northwest states,\nthe richest group la the union, to\nbe developed. It Is now where\nWashington and Oregon were 10 or\n15 years ago. It Aa .equal If not;\ngreater resources .than \"either of\nthose state and as there Is more de\nveloping to be done, there Is more\nopportunity for the man with capi\ntal or brains who Is capable of help\ning In that work and wants to do\nsomething for himself. Oar towns\natw-tmalWwr largest, city ha only.\n15.000 people, and yet we have-10\nmillion acres of good rich farm and\nfruit land, enough to .build twenty\ncities of 25.000 people and number\nless smaller one. beside. Idaho Is\nthe only arid state In the country\nwhich has all th water -..it needi.\nIn the Boise, Welser. Lost. Wood,\nPayette and great Snake rivers we\nhave an unequalled water supply\nfor our dry lands, It is only a ques\ntion of bow to get It on the land.\nThat ts being solved every dsy and\nthousands of acres of raw land are\nput under water every year. The\nfall in Idaho's rivers to great euough\nto allow of power sites all along\nand It will one day be the great\npower state. Our towns are grow\ning, our people are posperous n1\nthe future Is the best.\"\ndown ot car shops and ot the repair\nshops of the railroads, lessened de-\nnnfcnd for supplies and In general a\nbusiness depression.\nIn the face of these conditions\nstock brokers say, it la not surpris\ning that there should be a tendency\ntoward falling prices. A slump In\nTTntfnrt Rrntaa Rlnol TTnlnn Puclfln\nand Reading was no surprise to the I\nbrokers. Some wall street leaders\nassort that attempts on the part of\nthe big business interests to make\nHill's summing up of the case ap\npear true enough to Impress the In'\nterstate commerce commission, are\nreally responsible for the break.\nMany loaders are Inclined to re\ncard the break more as a warning\nthan as an Indication of real condl-f\ntlons. That It reflects the true at\ntitude of some of the financier!,\nhowever, .who are frankly alarmed\nat conditions, Is admitted by many\nmarket manipulators.\nJudging by the warnings already\ngiven out by the street, however,\nmany financiers are Inclined to con\nsider the whole matter As one of ex\ntreme gravity. It Is beltoved that\nthe railroads and their allied inter\nests, forming one of the most pow\nerful groups in the street, are de\ntermined to make a fight for higher\nrates, and that the fight will not\natop at small breaks In prices and\npredictions of financial difficulties if\nthe rates are not granted.\nf If It seems that the rates are not\nto. be allowed. It Is declared In some\nquarters that a genuine financial\nflury may be the result and that In\nsnlta of prosperity and the evident\nAmount of business already In .the\nhands of the railroads, conditions\nbordering on the panicky are not un\nlikely, Daring and skillful manipu\nlators. It (s Intimated, are enlisted\nIn the Ogbt. and the struggle Is apt\nto be reflected very cearly in mar\nket ceuters.\nii o\nWASHINGTON WOMEN\nAUK ENFRANCHISED\n\nckitbd rasss umssd win\nOlympla, Wash., Nov. i. Ward\npoliticians are polishing up their\nrusty manners and are reading up\non the art of making thenisolves\npleasing to women in Washington\nstate today, because the women are\nat last \"equal\" to men. When Oov-\neruor Hay appended his signature to\nthe proclamation presented to him\nLlate yesterday afternoon, he outran\nThlsed every wrman within the state\nwho has passed tbe age of II yean.\nTHEIR MARITAL\nTROUBLES ARE\nALL SETTLED\nThe marital troubles of the Klmsey\nfamily were given their final airing\nthis morning, when the wife, Mrs.\nCarrie Klmsey, with her attorney,\nCarey Martin, appeared before Judge\nGalloway and asked lor a decree or\ndivorce from ber husband, R. G. Klm\nsey, and also asked to be given the\noustody andi coutrol of her three\nchildren.\nHad a S of Trouble.\nThe domestic troubles of this couple\nnnd there was a soa of them first\nbegan to attract the attention of the\npubllo last August. They were mar\nried In March, 1800, and, while, ac\ncording to the complaint of the wife,\nthere bad been an abundance ot\ntrouble for some time, It was not un\ntil In July that the break came. She\nwas, so she says, ordered to leave ber\nhome, and, Just as she was preparing\nto do so, the husband kidnaped tbe\nchildren, and took them to bis moth\ner at Shaw. With her brother she\nwent to tbe grandmother's home and\ndemanded their return, and finally\nsuccomlod In securing the youngest,\nwhich was 17 months of age. The\nother two she did not secure.\nArrest Wife and 11 rot her.\nFollowing upon the heels of this, al\nleged kidnaping, the wife and ber\nbrother were arres'ed, at the Instance\nof tbe husband, upon a severe charge.\nbut were afterwards dismissed by the\ngrand jury.' In the time Intervening\nshe began a suit for divorce, charg\nlug crvitd and inhuman treatment, and\nthe husband came back with an an\nswer full of counter-charges, attack\ning ber character. Tbe evidence was\ntaken this morning, and she was\ngranted a divorce and the custody of\ntbe youngest child, but the custody of\nthe other two was awarded to the\nfather.\nThe husband did not appear In per\nson to contest tbe case, but was rep\nresented by an attorney.\nEverybody's New Campaign.\nCEx-Senator Frank J. Cannon on th\nMormons.)\nChlldron Cry\nFOR FLETCHER'S\nCASTORI A\nA Regular Tom IVy.\nWas Buslt climbing rees and\nfences, Jumping ditches, whltllng. al\nways setting scratches, cuts, sprains,\nbruises, bumns. burns or scalds. Hut\nIsws! Her mother Just applied Arni\nca Salve and cured her quick. Heals\neverything heslable bolls, ulcers,\neoseiiis, old sores, corns or piles. Try\nIt, tbe, at 1. C. Perry's.\nEverybody's Magazine announce\na series, beginning with the Decem\nber lsBue, by Frank J. Cannon, form\nefty United States senator from Utah,\non the subject of Mormonlsm and\npolygamy. In 1890, the man who ts\nwriting these articles, himself a Mor\nmon, but not a polygamlst, went to\nWashington and saved his people\nfrom disfranchisement on the prom\nise that the doctrine and practise of\npolygamy were to be abandoned by\nthe Mormon church. A \"manifesto\"\nwas promulgated by which the Mor\nneon Prophet as the result of a\n\"divine revelation\" withdrew the doc\ntrine of polygamy from the practise\nof the faith. The emancipation of\ntheir people from hierarchical domi\nnation was promised and tbe right of\nstatehood finally obtained.\nThese pledges, says tbe writer',' are\nbeing openly violated. Polygamy 1\nstill rampant. Moreover, their lead\ners have capitalized their religious\nfaith, and are usli g the-superhuman\npower of a religious tyranny to In\ncrease the dividends of a national\nplunder. The Mormon people paJK a\nyearly tribute of more than two mil\nlion dollars lu tithes to Joseph F.\nSmith, and he ui.es that income to\nbis own ends, without an accounting.\nHe is president of the Utah branch of\nthe sugar trust, and of the lonl In\ncorporations of the salt trust,\nDKVKLOI'MIC.NT LKAUtE.\n(Continued from page 1.)\nPLACKS KXPORT Dl'TY\nON CHRISTMAS TItEKH\nDMITSB pssss ijiiip wins\nMontpolier, Vt.. Nov. 29. Aeon-\nservation measure that strikes a\nblow at Santa Claus Is expected to\ncome before th Vermont legisla\nture. Tbe present tax of five con's\non every Christmas tree shipped\nfrom the state will, If the measure\nIs adopted, be raised to 25 cents.\nIt Is bolieved thla will stop the ex\nportation of pine trees to the larg\ner cltlm of the East at ChrUtmua\ntime.\nLndy Cook, (nee Teiiiuee CUf\n1 1 ii of 1-ondon, sends us a copy uf\nber lecturci on morals. How did\nhu know about It?\nOn our opportunities\nAnd In a few more years we will\nbring tbe East to tear,\nDegglng bard for population If yoa\nplease.\nYell.\nWell well, whet th ell\nSalem's got a new hotel\nBy-gum!\nSong Tuue, \"Kings oa Her Fl-\ngers, etc.\"\nOregon for apples\nAnd all things that grow\nOregon for unity,\nLand of opportunity.\nOregon for railroads;\nOregon for wealth;\nOrtgon for development;\nOregon for health.\n'TIs Oregon for Frisco\nEXPO\n(Yell) 1915.\nYell.\nP. A. C.\nP. A. C.\nPortland Ad Club\nHully Gee!\nThe Portland Ad. Club came\nKalem this morning In a special\nabout 40 strong.\nto\ncar\nThe nrty million dollar railroad\nmerger melius nothing to tbe peopH\nbut scientific ektortlou of rui!tullsiu.","height":"25992","width":"20288"}}
